The raw data plots seems to indicate that the history of flooding is not associated with swamp timothy productivity. Conversely, those units that were disced in the previous three years had higher yields of swamp timothy than the units that were not tilled.

Analyze apparent effects of treatments

These analyses should be interpreted with caution. Apparent effects of treatments cannot be attributed to treatments because there was no randomization in the selection of units to be flooded. Based on my understanding of management decisions, flooding is decided on the basis of the potential of units to express higher production. Therefore, I am suspicious that there may be a selection bias in the results.

brm1 <- brm(st_g_m2 ~ act * y.flooded.15,
            data = qdt_mass_act_fld,
            iter = 4000,
            warmup = 1500,
            thin = 2,

  facet_wrap(~ Parameter, scales = "free")

All chains seem to have very similar distributions for all parameters. It looks like convergence to the same posterior has been achieved by all chains for all parameters.

brm1.mcmc %>%
  ggs() %>%
  ggs_traceplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ Parameter, scales = "free")

All traceplots seem to indicate good mixing and convergence.

Results

There is a clear differencee between units that were disced and those that were not. The posterior median difference is 168 g/m2 with a standard error of 25.7 g/m2.

A model including number of years flooded out of the last 15 showed evidence that the effect of flooding depended on tillage, whereby units without tillage had a small increase of yield with increasing number of years flooded but disced units had declining yields witin increasing number of years flooded.
